on the earlier phase. The late seventeenth and eighteenth centuries emerge as a dynamic time that saw, along with cultural persistence, many new adaptations and creations. Covering a period of over a century and a half, this study goes beyond a monolithic treatment of the region to introduce for the first time a systematic analysis of subregional variation in vocabulary and real-life phenomena, showing how, within larger regional trends, each tiniest community of the Toluca Valley retained markers of its individuality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEthnohistoryzMexicozToluca Valley. 0aIndians of MexicozMexicozToluca ValleyxSocial life and customsy17th century. 0aIndians of MexicozMexicozToluca ValleyxSocial life and customsy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804784993zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804784993423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804784993.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles